⦿ .spun — the five-fold spin of The Preface to Cesar
node N1 · N1 · ⟦The Preface to Cesar:N1:da6c86⟧

WHO   — The Preface to Cesar — the testament of the seer
WHAT  — The author's own key to the Centuries — a father's testament on prophecy, divine inspiration, the limits of astrology, and why the future had to be written in riddles. The single most important guide to how Nostradamus wanted his work understood.
WHERE — N1 · Nostradamus  Framework inputs: Les Propheties (1555)  Conductor / external anchor: ROOT0 (catalogued into UD0)
WHY   — Because a book of veiled prophecy needs a preface that names the veil; because Nostradamus wished his son — and posterity — to know the verses came (he claimed) from a divine fire and not from sorcery; because he meant to instruct his readers in how to read, and to absolve himself before the Church.
HOW   — As a tender, anxious, deliberately obscure letter — part confession, part apologia — written near March 1555, weaving scripture, astrology, humility, and warning; declaring some things kept hidden on purpose, lest they fall to the powerful or the profane.

awareness — what the node knows of itself:
  I write to you, my son, what I dared not say plainly to the world — the fire is real, the words are veiled, and the reading is yours.

